<doc id="282" url="https://en.wikivoyage.org/wiki?curid=282" title="Afrikaans phrasebook">
<h1>Afrikaans phrasebook</h1>
&lt;templatestyles src="Pagebanner/styles.css"/&gt;
♡❤♡Afrikaans♡❤♡ is spoken throughout &lt;a href="South%20Africa"&gt;South Africa&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="Namibia"&gt;Namibia&lt;/a&gt;. The language is mainly derived from &lt;a href="Dutch%20phrasebook"&gt;Dutch&lt;/a&gt;. However, most Afrikaans speakers in the workplace have some knowledge of English.

<h2>Pronunciation guide</h2>
<h3>Vowels</h3>
<dl>
BULLET::::- a : as in s♡❤♡u♡❤♡n
BULLET::::- e : as in m♡❤♡e♡❤♡t but sometimes as in m♡❤♡ee♡❤♡t or ang♡❤♡e♡❤♡l
BULLET::::- ê : as in ♡❤♡a♡❤♡pple
BULLET::::- ë : usually pronounced the same as 'e', but when it is accented due to grammar, such as in words like 'geëet' which means 'to have eaten', it can be pronounced three other ways: m♡❤♡ee♡❤♡t, f♡❤♡ea♡❤♡r or ♡❤♡we♡❤♡t
BULLET::::- i : as in b♡❤♡i♡❤♡t
BULLET::::- o : as in f♡❤♡o♡❤♡rt or m♡❤♡oo♡❤♡d or b♡❤♡oy♡❤♡
BULLET::::- ô : as in c♡❤♡au♡❤♡ldron
BULLET::::- u : as in ♡❤u♡❤ in h♡❤♡u♡❤♡t with rounded lips
BULLET::::- y : no equivalent in English but similar to y in m♡❤♡y♡❤♡, same as Dutch ♡❤ij♡❤,
BULLET::::- 'n : in 'a' as in ♡❤♡'a♡❤♡ dog' or ♡❤♡'a♡❤♡ song'. This is the article; it is never capitalised even if used at the start of a sentence: the word that follows is capitalised.

</dl>
Note that Afrikaans pronunciation is extremely difficult and can be a challenge, even for &lt;a href="Dutch"&gt;Dutch&lt;/a&gt; speakers.

<h3>Consonants</h3>
<dl>
BULLET::::- b : as in ♡❤♡b♡❤♡at
BULLET::::- c : as in ♡❤♡k♡❤♡ing (uncommon, usually proper nouns e.g. 'Coetzee'
BULLET::::- d : as in ♡❤♡d♡❤♡ance but pronounced as English 't' at the end of words
BULLET::::- f : as in ♡❤♡f♡❤♡an
BULLET::::- g : similarly to the 'ch' in ba♡❤♡ch♡❤♡, but a lot harder and more glottal - a bit like hawking up phlegm :-).
BULLET::::- h : as in ♡❤♡h♡❤♡at
BULLET::::- j : as in ♡❤♡y♡❤♡ak
BULLET::::- k : as in ♡❤♡k♡❤♡ing
BULLET::::- l : as in ♡❤♡l♡❤♡amp
BULLET::::- m : as in ♡❤♡m♡❤♡an
BULLET::::- n : as in ♡❤♡n♡❤♡ap
BULLET::::- p : as in ♡❤♡p♡❤♡et
BULLET::::- r : as in ♡❤♡r♡❤♡ant, but the sound is rolled
BULLET::::- s : as in ♡❤♡s♡❤♡et
BULLET::::- t : as in ♡❤♡t♡❤♡ale
BULLET::::- v : same as the English 'f'
BULLET::::- w : pronounced the same as the English 'v' as in ♡❤♡v♡❤♡et
BULLET::::- x : as in fi♡❤♡x♡❤♡ but extremely rare, usually found in scientific terms or loanwords.
BULLET::::- z : as in blit♡❤♡z♡❤♡

</dl>
In some loan words, 'g', 'v' and 'w' may be pronounced the same as their English equivalents, but this is uncommon.

<h3>Digraphs and trigraphs</h3>
<dl>
BULLET::::- aa : as in f♡❤♡a♡❤♡ther
BULLET::::- ae : two sounds, one after another, quite quickly. Starts as 'aa' and is quickly finished off with the Afrikaans 'a' as in d♡❤♡u♡❤♡st
BULLET::::- ch : can be pronounced in three ways: lo♡❤♡ch♡❤♡ or ♡❤♡sh♡❤♡ine or ♡❤♡k♡❤♡ing
BULLET::::- kk : as in ♡❤♡c♡❤♡ane
BULLET::::- nn : as in ma♡❤♡n♡❤♡
BULLET::::- sj : as in ma♡❤♡ch♡❤♡ine
BULLET::::- ee : as in f♡❤♡ea♡❤♡r
BULLET::::- eë : as in f♡❤♡ea♡❤♡r but pronounced as two separate sounds. Sounds almost like 'ee-ye'
BULLET::::- ië : same as eë
BULLET::::- ei : as is s♡❤♡a♡❤♡le
BULLET::::- eu : pronounced two ways: as in ♡❤♡ea♡❤♡r or as in m♡❤♡ew♡❤♡
BULLET::::- gh : same as English 'gh'. For example: ♡❤♡gh♡❤♡ost
BULLET::::- ll : as in ♡❤♡l♡❤♡amp
BULLET::::- mm : as in ♡❤♡m♡❤♡end
BULLET::::- ie : pronounced either as long 'ee' like in br♡❤♡ee♡❤♡d or as 'i' in s♡❤♡i♡❤♡ck
BULLET::::- kn : as in pi♡❤♡ck 'n♡❤♡ pay
BULLET::::- ng : as in si♡❤♡ng♡❤♡
BULLET::::- nk : as in thi♡❤♡nk♡❤♡
BULLET::::- oe : pronounced either as the long 'oo' as in l♡❤♡oo♡❤♡t or as a short 'oo' as in f♡❤♡oo♡❤♡t
BULLET::::- oë : as in English d♡❤♡oe♡❤♡r
BULLET::::- oo : same as German "ü", make your lips into the position of "o" but say "ee" instead.
BULLET::::- ou : as in c♡❤♡oa♡❤♡t
BULLET::::- rs : like fa♡❤♡rse♡❤♡, but the 'r' is rolled
BULLET::::- tj : as in ♡❤♡ch♡❤♡unk
BULLET::::- tj : combined with ♡❤♡ie♡❤♡ as in ♡❤♡ki♡❤♡d
BULLET::::- ui : also a unique sound. Sounds like pl♡❤♡ay♡❤♡ but with pouted lips. The name sh♡❤♡a♡❤♡ne is the closest English equivalent
BULLET::::- uu : similar to German ♡❤♡ü♡❤♡ber but pronounced with more emphasis and much longer. Identical to the final 'yy' sound
BULLET::::- aai : like the 'y' in sh♡❤♡y♡❤♡, but a pronounced a lot longer.
BULLET::::- eeu : A unique trigraph. The closest English equivalent is the English word ewe. Try blending the sounds 'ew' and 'oo'
BULLET::::- oei : similar to ph♡❤♡ooey♡❤♡ but pronounced with a rapid 'w' in it
BULLET::::- ooi : similar to ♡❤♡oi♡❤♡l but pronounced with a rapid 'w' in it
BULLET::::- uie : similar to pl♡❤♡aye♡❤♡r but pronounced much longer

</dl>
<h3>Note on Afrikaans</h3>

Like English, double consonants in Afrikaans are pronounced as a single sound, and not two separate sounds, unless occurring at a syllabary break: 'wekker': 'vack-er' (alarm clock) but 'melkkoei': 'melk-koo-ee' (milking cow).

Note that although Afrikaans digraphs and trigraphs contain mostly vowels and sound as though they contain many syllables, they in fact are seen as a single syllable.

For example, the word 'Goeie' sounds as if it contains 3 syllables, but in fact contains only two: 'goei' and 'e' are the 2 syllables.

From this, you can see Afrikaans pronunciation, like English for a foreigner, can be rather irregular. Pronunciation can be hard and the accent is extremely difficult to master, but when spoken correctly, Afrikaans is the most melodic Germanic language.

However, one should not be daunted. Afrikaans grammar is really quite simple and is more similar to English than to any other Germanic language. Verbs are even simpler than English: there is no ♡❤am♡❤ or ♡❤are♡❤ or ♡❤were♡❤ but only ♡❤is♡❤ and ♡❤was♡❤.

One who is learning Afrikaans will probably catch onto it rather quickly and will have no problem with speaking &lt;a href="Dutch"&gt;Dutch&lt;/a&gt; or understanding &lt;a href="German"&gt;German&lt;/a&gt;.

<h2>Important differences between Dutch and Afrikaans</h2>

A ♡❤rukkie♡❤ in Afrikaans is a short period of time, not a sexual act performed on oneself.

Common use examples are ♡❤Ek gaan 'n rukkie slaap♡❤ or ♡❤Ek sal oor 'n rukkie daar wees♡❤

♡❤Baie♡❤ means ♡❤veel♡❤ (many); however, the word ♡❤veel♡❤ also exists in Afrikaans and has the same meaning.

